<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1893-12-05T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1893-12-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="490" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d490">
                    <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Uhl</persName> to Mr.
                                <persName type="to">McDonald</persName>.</hi></head>
                    <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department
                                    of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1893-12-05"><hi rend="italic">December 5,
                            1893</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        <seg rendition="#left">No. 30.]</seg></opener>
                    <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have received your No. 27, of 26th October
                        last, in further relation to the anxiety of the Christians at Oroomiah—among
                        them, <pb facs="0616" n="508" xml:id="pg_508"/> as your No. 28 indicates,
                        being over thirty Americans—occasioned by the atrocious murder of the
                        Armenian Christian Aga Jan Khan, at that place.</p>
                    <p>You will please apprise the foreign office of the high appreciation with
                        which this Government learns of His Majesty’s benevolent interest in the
                        matter and of the steps taken to protect our citizens.</p>
                    <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                    <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Edwin F. Uhl</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Acting Secretary.</hi></signed></closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>